## The problem with distributed transactions

You cannot use a single `@Transactional` across three separate databases. 2-Phase Commit (2PC) exists but creates tight coupling — if the coordinator crashes, all participants block indefinitely.

```text
2PC problem:
  Phase 1: Coordinator asks all services "are you ready?"
  Phase 2: Coordinator says "commit"

  If coordinator crashes between Phase 1 and 2:
    → All services LOCKED, waiting forever
    → Your order, inventory, and payment are all stuck
```

The industry solution: **Saga Pattern** — a sequence of local transactions where each step publishes an event, and failures trigger compensating transactions.

---

## Understand this first: two Saga styles

```text
CHOREOGRAPHY (event-driven):          ORCHESTRATION (central coordinator):

Order → event → Inventory reacts       Order Saga Orchestrator
Inventory → event → Payment reacts       → calls Inventory
Payment → event → Order confirmed         → calls Payment
                                           → calls Order confirm
No central brain                        Central brain (Saga orchestrator)
Harder to trace                         Easier to trace
Good for 2-3 steps                     Good for 5+ steps
```

---

## Choreography Saga — implementation

### Step 1: Order service starts the saga

```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class OrderService {

    private final OrderRepository orderRepo;
    private final KafkaTemplate<String, Object> kafka;

    @Transactional
    public Order placeOrder(OrderRequest request) {
        // Save order in PENDING state locally
        Order order = Order.builder()
            .userId(request.getUserId())
            .items(request.getItems())
            .totalAmount(request.getTotal())
            .status(OrderStatus.PENDING)   // not CONFIRMED yet
            .build();
        orderRepo.save(order);

        // Publish event — Inventory service will react
        kafka.send("order.created", order.getId().toString(),
            new OrderCreatedEvent(order.getId(), request.getItems(), request.getTotal()));

        log.info("Order {} created in PENDING state", order.getId());
        return order;
    }

    // Called when payment succeeds
    @KafkaListener(topics = "payment.succeeded", groupId = "order-service")
    @Transactional
    public void onPaymentSucceeded(PaymentSucceededEvent event) {
        orderRepo.findById(event.getOrderId()).ifPresent(order -> {
            order.setStatus(OrderStatus.CONFIRMED);
            orderRepo.save(order);
            log.info("Order {} CONFIRMED after payment success", order.getId());
        });
    }

    // Compensating transaction: undo the order
    @KafkaListener(topics = "payment.failed", groupId = "order-service")
    @Transactional
    public void onPaymentFailed(PaymentFailedEvent event) {
        orderRepo.findById(event.getOrderId()).ifPresent(order -> {
            order.setStatus(OrderStatus.CANCELLED);
            orderRepo.save(order);
            log.warn("Order {} CANCELLED due to payment failure", order.getId());
        });
    }
}
```

### Step 2: Inventory service reacts and reserves stock

```java
@Component
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class InventoryConsumer {

    private final InventoryRepository inventoryRepo;
    private final KafkaTemplate<String, Object> kafka;

    @KafkaListener(topics = "order.created", groupId = "inventory-service")
    @Transactional
    public void onOrderCreated(OrderCreatedEvent event) {
        try {
            // Try to reserve items
            for (OrderItem item : event.getItems()) {
                Inventory inv = inventoryRepo.findByProductId(item.getProductId())
                    .orElseThrow(() -> new OutOfStockException(item.getProductId()));

                if (inv.getAvailable() < item.getQuantity()) {
                    throw new OutOfStockException("Insufficient stock for " + item.getProductId());
                }
                inv.setAvailable(inv.getAvailable() - item.getQuantity());
                inv.setReserved(inv.getReserved() + item.getQuantity());
                inventoryRepo.save(inv);
            }

            // Success: trigger payment
            kafka.send("inventory.reserved", event.getOrderId().toString(),
                new InventoryReservedEvent(event.getOrderId(), event.getTotalAmount()));
            log.info("Inventory reserved for order {}", event.getOrderId());

        } catch (OutOfStockException e) {
            // Compensating event: tell order service to cancel
            kafka.send("inventory.failed", event.getOrderId().toString(),
                new InventoryFailedEvent(event.getOrderId(), e.getMessage()));
            log.warn("Inventory reservation FAILED for order {}: {}", event.getOrderId(), e.getMessage());
        }
    }

    // Compensating transaction: release reserved stock
    @KafkaListener(topics = "payment.failed", groupId = "inventory-service")
    @Transactional
    public void onPaymentFailed(PaymentFailedEvent event) {
        // Undo inventory reservation
        for (OrderItem item : event.getItems()) {
            inventoryRepo.findByProductId(item.getProductId()).ifPresent(inv -> {
                inv.setAvailable(inv.getAvailable() + item.getQuantity());
                inv.setReserved(inv.getReserved() - item.getQuantity());
                inventoryRepo.save(inv);
            });
        }
        log.info("Inventory reservation RELEASED for order {} (payment failed)", event.getOrderId());
    }
}
```

---

## Saga event flow

```text
HAPPY PATH:
Order.PENDING → [order.created] → Inventory.reserved → [inventory.reserved]
  → Payment.charged → [payment.succeeded] → Order.CONFIRMED

FAILURE PATH (out of stock):
Order.PENDING → [order.created] → Inventory FAILS → [inventory.failed]
  → Order.CANCELLED

FAILURE PATH (payment declined):
Order.PENDING → [order.created] → Inventory.reserved → [inventory.reserved]
  → Payment FAILS → [payment.failed] → Inventory RELEASED → Order.CANCELLED
```

---

## Expected Kafka log output (happy path)

```text
10:30:01.123 INFO  OrderService         - Order abc-123 created in PENDING state
10:30:01.145 INFO  InventoryConsumer    - Inventory reserved for order abc-123
10:30:01.189 INFO  PaymentConsumer      - Payment charged for order abc-123: $99.99
10:30:01.201 INFO  OrderService         - Order abc-123 CONFIRMED after payment success
```

**Expected Kafka log (failure — out of stock):**
```text
10:30:05.001 INFO  OrderService         - Order xyz-456 created in PENDING state
10:30:05.018 WARN  InventoryConsumer    - Inventory reservation FAILED for order xyz-456: Insufficient stock for PROD-001
10:30:05.031 WARN  OrderService         - Order xyz-456 CANCELLED due to inventory failure
```

---

## Your interview answer

> "The Saga pattern replaces distributed transactions with a sequence of local transactions connected by events. Each step either succeeds and publishes an event, or fails and triggers a compensating transaction to undo previous steps. I used choreography-based Saga with Kafka: order service emits order.created, inventory service reacts and either emits inventory.reserved or inventory.failed. The key insight is that every step must be idempotent — if the same event is processed twice, the result must be the same."

---

## Idempotency — prevent double processing

```java
@KafkaListener(topics = "inventory.reserved", groupId = "payment-service")
@Transactional
public void onInventoryReserved(InventoryReservedEvent event) {
    // Idempotency check — don't charge twice for the same order
    if (paymentRepo.existsByOrderId(event.getOrderId())) {
        log.info("Payment already processed for order {} — skipping", event.getOrderId());
        return;
    }
    // Proceed with charging
    chargeAndPublishResult(event);
}
```

followUps.answer:
**Choreography** (each service knows what to do next):
```text
Order Service → emits order.created
  Inventory Service listens → reserves stock → emits inventory.reserved
  Payment Service listens → charges card → emits payment.succeeded
  Order Service listens → confirms order

Advantage: Decoupled, no central coordinator
Disadvantage: Hard to trace the saga flow. "Where is this order right now?" requires checking 3 services
```

**Orchestration** (central brain coordinates all steps):
```java
@Component  // The Saga Orchestrator
public class OrderSagaOrchestrator {

    public void execute(OrderRequest request) {
        // Orchestrator explicitly calls each step
        String orderId = orderService.createPending(request);

        try {
            inventoryService.reserve(orderId, request.getItems());
        } catch (OutOfStockException e) {
            orderService.cancel(orderId, "Out of stock");
            return;
        }

        try {
            paymentService.charge(orderId, request.getTotal());
        } catch (PaymentException e) {
            inventoryService.release(orderId, request.getItems()); // compensate
            orderService.cancel(orderId, "Payment failed");
            return;
        }

        orderService.confirm(orderId);
    }
}
```

**Advantage**: Easy to trace — the orchestrator IS the saga flow.
**Disadvantage**: Central orchestrator is a coupling point; if it goes down, sagas stall.

**When to choose**:
- Choreography: 2-3 steps, services that can evolve independently, event-driven mindset
- Orchestration: 5+ steps, complex rollback logic, need a single place to audit saga state
- Framework: **Axon Framework** or **Temporal** for orchestration-based sagas in Java

