**Problem with local (in-memory) rate limiting across multiple instances:**

```text
You have 10 pods. Rate limit: 100 req/min per API key.
If each pod limits to 100 independently:
  → Client can make 1000 req/min (100 × 10 pods) — 10x the intended limit!
```

**Fix: shared state in Redis (centralized counter)**

All approaches that use Redis as the counter backend automatically handle this:

```java
// Redis INCR — atomic, shared across all instances
String key = "ratelimit:" + apiKey + ":" + minuteBucket();
Long count = redis.opsForValue().increment(key);
redis.expire(key, 60, TimeUnit.SECONDS);  // only set on first call
return count <= MAX_REQUESTS;

private String minuteBucket() {
    return String.valueOf(System.currentTimeMillis() / 60000);
}
```

**Redis INCR is atomic**: Even with 10 pods calling it simultaneously, the counter is accurate. No race conditions.

**Lua script approach (INCR + EXPIRE atomically):**
```java
// Redis Lua script runs atomically — no race condition between INCR and EXPIRE
String luaScript =
    "local count = redis.call('INCR', KEYS[1])\n" +
    "if count == 1 then redis.call('EXPIRE', KEYS[1], ARGV[1]) end\n" +
    "return count";

Long count = redis.execute(
    RedisScript.of(luaScript, Long.class),
    List.of(key),
    String.valueOf(windowSeconds));
return count <= maxRequests;
```

**If Redis goes down**: Fail open (allow all requests) or fail closed (block all). Most APIs fail open — better to risk some extra traffic than to block legitimate users.

**N+1 problem**: You fetch N records, then for each record you make 1 additional query — N+1 queries total instead of 1 or 2.

```java
// ❌ N+1 — loads 100 orders, then 1 query per order to load user
List<Order> orders = orderRepo.findByStatus("PENDING"); // 1 query
for (Order o : orders) {
    System.out.println(o.getUser().getEmail()); // 100 queries!
}
// Total: 101 queries instead of 1
```

This happens because `User` is lazily loaded by default in JPA.

**Fix 1 — JOIN FETCH in JPQL:**
```java
@Query("SELECT o FROM Order o JOIN FETCH o.user WHERE o.status = :status")
List<Order> findByStatusWithUser(@Param("status") String status);
// 1 query with JOIN — loads orders + users together
```

**Fix 2 — @EntityGraph:**
```java
@EntityGraph(attributePaths = {"user", "items"})
List<Order> findByStatus(String status);
// Spring generates JOIN FETCH automatically
```

**Fix 3 — Batch fetching (for collections):**
```java
