## What the audit found

```text
Current state:
  Access token TTL: 24 hours   ← stolen token works for a full day
  Refresh token:    no expiry  ← stolen refresh token works forever
  Logout:           client just deletes token locally, server doesn't know
  Password change:  old tokens still valid

Risk: attacker who steals a token has access for up to 24 hours (or forever)
```

---

## The fix — short-lived tokens + refresh rotation + blacklist

```text
FIXED state:
  Access token TTL:  15 minutes    ← stolen token useful for max 15 min
  Refresh token TTL: 7 days        ← limited window, single-use
  Logout:            blacklist the refresh token in Redis
  Password change:   blacklist ALL user's tokens by incrementing token version
```

---

## Step 1 — JWT service with short TTL

```java
@Component
public class JwtService {

    @Value("${security.jwt.access-token-secret}")  // from Vault/Secrets Manager
    private String accessTokenSecret;

    @Value("${security.jwt.refresh-token-secret}")
    private String refreshTokenSecret;

    private static final long ACCESS_TOKEN_TTL_MS  = 15 * 60 * 1000L;    // 15 minutes
    private static final long REFRESH_TOKEN_TTL_MS = 7 * 24 * 3600 * 1000L; // 7 days

    public String generateAccessToken(User user) {
        return Jwts.builder()
            .setSubject(user.getId().toString())
            .claim("email",   user.getEmail())
            .claim("roles",   user.getRoles())
            .claim("version", user.getTokenVersion())  // for mass invalidation
            .setIssuedAt(new Date())
            .setExpiration(new Date(System.currentTimeMillis() + ACCESS_TOKEN_TTL_MS))
            .signWith(getSigningKey(accessTokenSecret), SignatureAlgorithm.HS256)
            .compact();
    }

    public String generateRefreshToken(User user) {
        return Jwts.builder()
            .setSubject(user.getId().toString())
            .setId(UUID.randomUUID().toString())  // unique JTI for blacklisting
            .claim("version", user.getTokenVersion())
            .setIssuedAt(new Date())
            .setExpiration(new Date(System.currentTimeMillis() + REFRESH_TOKEN_TTL_MS))
            .signWith(getSigningKey(refreshTokenSecret), SignatureAlgorithm.HS256)
            .compact();
    }

    public Claims validateToken(String token, boolean isRefresh) {
        try {
            return Jwts.parserBuilder()
                .setSigningKey(getSigningKey(isRefresh ? refreshTokenSecret : accessTokenSecret))
                .build()
                .parseClaimsJws(token)
                .getBody();
        } catch (ExpiredJwtException e) {
            throw new TokenExpiredException("Token has expired");
        } catch (JwtException e) {
            throw new InvalidTokenException("Invalid token: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }

    private SecretKey getSigningKey(String secret) {
        return Keys.hmacShaKeyFor(Decoders.BASE64.decode(secret));
    }
}
```

**Why store `version` in the token**: When user changes password, increment `user.tokenVersion` in DB. Every active token with old version is immediately invalid — no need to track individual tokens.

