**Scenario**: User opens the mobile app after 30 minutes offline. Their 15-minute access token is expired. What happens?

**Standard flow:**
```text
1. App makes API call → gets 401 Unauthorized
2. App detects 401 → tries to refresh using stored refresh token
3. If refresh succeeds → new access token issued, retry original request
4. If refresh fails (refresh token also expired) → force logout, send to login screen
```

**Client-side implementation (Android/React Native):**
```java
// Retrofit interceptor for automatic token refresh
public class AuthInterceptor implements Interceptor {

    @Override
    public Response intercept(Chain chain) throws IOException {
        Request request = chain.request()
            .newBuilder()
            .header("Authorization", "Bearer " + tokenStore.getAccessToken())
            .build();

        Response response = chain.proceed(request);

        if (response.code() == 401) {
            response.close();

            // Refresh the token
            synchronized (this) {  // prevent concurrent refreshes
                String newToken = authService.refreshToken(tokenStore.getRefreshToken());
                if (newToken != null) {
                    tokenStore.saveAccessToken(newToken);
                    // Retry with new token
                    return chain.proceed(request.newBuilder()
                        .header("Authorization", "Bearer " + newToken)
                        .build());
                } else {
                    // Refresh failed → force logout
                    EventBus.getDefault().post(new LogoutEvent());
                    return response;
                }
            }
        }
        return response;
    }
}
```

**Silent refresh in web apps**: Refresh 2-3 minutes BEFORE expiry (read `exp` claim, set timer):
